items.title: Platylobium parviflorum
items.content_text: Part of the old Platylobium formosum s.l. group.

items.title: Cotula coronopifolia
items.content_text: Taller than usual and with undivided leaves.

items.title: Polyscias sambucifolia subsp. 1
items.content_text: Broadest leaves I've seen on this taxon.

items.title: Schoenus spp.
items.content_text: Flowers on long stalks. Possibly S. brevifolius.

items.title: Comesperma defoliatum
items.content_text: About 50cm tall, leafless, often with just one flower.

items.title: Epacris paludosa
items.content_text: On the 2nd pic the glabrous style can be seen, which distinguishes it from the otherwise almost identical E. lanuginosa.

items.title: Blechnum minus
items.content_text: Young plant - looks like a Pellaea but isn't.

items.title: Sannantha pluriflora
items.content_text: Used to be Baeckea virgata and has recently changed name again from Babingtonia pluriflora (via Babingtonia virgata) to Sannantha pluriflora!

items.title: Candalides hyacinthina hyacinthina, Lobelia gibbosa s.s.
Goodenia elongata
items.content_text: Growing in wet edge of swamp.

items.title: Lobelia gibbosa s.s.
items.content_text: First time I've been able to ID this species. Leaves not obviously lobed (so not L. dentata). Under the microscope, seed was 0.2-0.3mm long, reticulate, not 3-angled (so not L. simplicicaulis).

items.title: Spiranthes australis s.l.
items.content_text: Edge of a small remnant swamp.

items.title: Hypericum japonicum
items.content_text: Mat-forming and small flowers compared to H. gramineum. Growing in damp gully.

items.title: Arrhenechthites mixtus
items.content_text: One flower remaining on one plant, showing purple flower. Map shows the approximate extent of the 20 or so plants seen.

items.title: Angophora floribunda
items.content_text: Showing 2 features that separate Angophora from Eucalyptus ... opposite leaves and no operculum.

items.title: Utricularia dichotoma s.l., Utricularia dichotoma s.s.
Apium prostratum subsp. prostratum var. prostratum
tags: id~Apium prostratum subsp. prostratum var. prostratum

items.title: Kennedia rubicunda
items.content_text: Kennedia leaves are bottom left of photo. Climbing on Pittosporum undulatum.

items.title: Corybas fimbriatus
items.content_text: A rare plant, not recorded at this well-documented spot previously.

items.title: Cakile maritima subsp. maritima
items.content_text: Subtle differences in fruit shape is the keying feature.

items.title: Cakile maritima subsp. maritima
items.content_text: Subtle differences in fruit shape is the keying feature.

items.title: Glossodia minor
items.content_text: Just two plants seen - no others seen anywhere during two weeks of walks in the region.

items.title: Pomaderris ferruginea
items.content_text: Small cluster of plants sticking their head up above the heathland flora. Only one group of plants seen.

items.title: Dianella revoluta s.l.
items.content_text: No idea what this might be called at the moment.

items.title: Leptospermum trinervium
items.content_text: Silky-glabrescent leaves suggest trinervium but could be laevigatum?

items.title: Caesia parviflora var. parviflora
items.content_text: The var. parviflora is a bit of a guess based on Flora of Victoria key. Memory of plants is they were considerably taller than 20cm and flowers same size as I'm used to here in the Macedon Range. So fits var. parviflora.

items.title: Hybanthus vernonii subsp. vernonii
items.content_text: Single flower per plant/branch, one petal per flower.

items.title: Thelymitra X irregularis
items.content_text: A natural hybrid of and found growing with T. ixioides s.s. (observation 4156) and T. carnea (4157). Two extremes of 'spots' on different plants  pictured here.

items.title: Dockrillia striolata subsp. striolata
items.content_text: Literally growing on a rock. Location approximate.

items.title: Gahnia clarkei
items.content_text: Not positive of ID - G. sieberiana has been found locally.

items.title: Blechnum nudum
items.content_text: Not sure of ID. Location approximate.

items.title: Tetragonia tetragonioides
items.content_text: Sessile flower a good ID feature. Noteworthy is the extremely hairy stems which is apparently not common in this species.

items.title: Plantae spp.
items.content_text: Closest I can think of is Ricinocarpus pinifolius but greyish foliage doesn't fit.

items.title: Brachyscome aculeata
items.content_text: Basal leaves withered/gone. Stem leaves lobed towards leaf tip. Location approximate.

items.title: Goodenia elongata
items.content_text: Not sure of ID but seems to fit.

items.title: Paracaleana minor
items.content_text: Growing in centre of Barracoota Track, not far from Caleana major. Location approximate.

items.title: Hakea decurrens subsp. platytaenia
items.content_text: Not sure of ID. Fruit appears very wide compared to typical subsp. physocarpa. Location approximate.

items.title: Xyris operculata
items.content_text: I returned to this spot on Jan 23 2014 and obtained pic3 which is the ID feature (bracts in many rows, large at the top and getting progressively smaller to the bottom). Plants about 50cm tall growing in a short sandy section of the track.

items.title: Hibbertia riparia
items.content_text: Not sure of ID. Leaves look long for H. riparia but nothing else seems to fit? Location approximate.

items.title: Dianella aff. caerulea (Mallacoota)
items.content_text: Tall, lanky with aerial shoots. Location approximate.

items.title: Lepidosperma concavum
items.content_text: Not sure of ID. Narrow culms, shorter than or equal to leaf length.

items.title: Carpobrotus glaucescens
items.content_text: Not sure of ID. Could be C. rossii.

items.title: Cryptostylis spp.
items.content_text: Unusual flower (possibly past its best) but basal leaf doesn't fit? Returned in later years but not found again.
